metadata.name: Puzzles of the mind #18
metadata.description:
This is abstract art based on mathematical structure.
The puzzle of your mind seems broken and rearranged.

Mode has 2 variations.
 - Normal
 - Black
Color has 3 variations.
 - 常磐-tokiwa- (Green)
 - 真朱-shinshu- (Red)
 - 紺碧-konpeki- (Blue)
Color Level has 2 variations.
 - High
 - Low
Square Size has 3 variations.
 - Small
 - Middle
 - Large

Tokiwa is a Japanese word meaning always the same. It's green like the color of evergreen leaves.

Shinshu is a Japanese word that refers to a dull red color like vermilion. It means vermilion in its natural state with nothing mixed in.

Konpeki is a Japanese word that describes a deep blue, very close to azure. It's like a clear sky with summer sunshine.

Controls (in live view):
 - Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
 - Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
 - Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js

metadata.name: Millefoglie #346
metadata.description:
"A mille-feuille (French pronunciation: ​[mil fœj], "thousand-sheets"), also known by the names Napoleon, vanilla slice, and custard slice, is a dessert made of puff pastry layered with pastry cream. Its modern form was influenced by improvements made by Marie-Antoine Carême.

Traditionally, a mille-feuille is made up of three layers of puff pastry (pâte feuilletée), alternating with two layers of pastry cream (crème pâtissière). The top pastry layer is finished in various ways: sometimes it is topped with whipped cream, or it may be dusted with icing sugar, cocoa, pastry crumbs, or sliced almonds. It may also be glazed with icing or fondant alone, or in alternating white (icing) and brown (chocolate) or other colored icing stripes, and combed to create a marbled effect." — Wikipedia

Prints available upon request: prints@stefancontiero.com
Best enjoyed on browsers supporting Display-P3 color gamut.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

@stefan_contiero

metadata.name: Before/After #234
metadata.description:
A visual representation of a non-linear transformation. Each line connects a data point before the transformation has been applied to its corresponding point after the transformation has been applied. Switch to debug mode to see the untransformed and transformed points. Outline mode shows only the lines and can be used for plotting. (Plotting will likely work best on outputs where the total number of lines is low.)

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript, with the compute-intensive transformation (t-SNE) implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. The final artwork is a static SVG file that can be downloaded and displayed at any resolution. No external libraries have been used.

More information about this collection is provided here: https://clauswilke.com/art/project/before-after

I would like to thank Bartholomew Littlesilver for helpful artistic feedback, Liam Egan for help with creating plottable SVGs, and BRUTALISTI and neophob for encouraging me to pursue AssemblyScript for implementing performance-critical code.

Press 'm' to cycle between normal, debug, and outline mode.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Boro #34
metadata.description:
Boro is inspired by the Japanese mending technique of the same name, which means something mended, in particular something mended with small pieces of fabric and patterned over stitching. The technique makes the fabric both stronger and more beautiful.

To render at different resolutions please use keyboard characters 1 to 5, which will render the artwork at a square of 1000 to 5000 respectively.

metadata.name: Textile Bacteria #171
metadata.description:
Telar's code became self-aware and tried to escape. I built a containment unit. "Textile Bacteria" is the result.

--

The piece is based on the 1970's work of the British mathematician John Conway's "Conway's Game of Life" cellular automaton. To avoid bacteria from dying when one of the threads ends up entirely on top of the other the algorithm adds one pseudorandom artificial cross in the weaving feeding the creatures keeping at the same time the weave consistent.

- Left-click to feed dead bacteria.
- Use the arrow keys to flip between the face and the back of the fabric.
- Press 'SPACE' on your keyboard to pause/play. 
- Press 'ENTER' on your keyboard to rewind. 
- Press 'F' on your keyboard to toggle between full-screen and regular view. 
- Press 'S' on your keyboard to save it as a 36 megapixels print.

metadata.name: 0.20 carat #406
metadata.description:
I come from a family of gemstones merchants going back a hundred years. In fact, I’m of the first generation who did not pursue the career. The carat series is my way to pay homage to this heritage.

The 0.20 carat collection is dedicated to my mother. Her lifetime passion for precious stones and their beauty inspired my aesthetic sensibility and led me to become an artist. 

Love,
Raphaël

metadata.name: FUTURE BASTARDS #78
FUTURE BASTARDS #113
Oceans of Anxiety #33
metadata.description:
Fully generated by code on your machine. Variety of palletes and styles hand-picked with love and understanding.

Anxiety comes in waves.
It’s that sense of unidentifiable dread.
It can feel like you’re in the middle of an ocean on a rocking boat, and on those really bad days there isn’t even a lifebuoy, you’re drowning and can’t catch your breath, time is viscous and moving in slow-motion.

This piece does not set out to necessarily convey only the worst of dealing with anxiety, but also the resolutions and relief when it’s not there, or finally lets you go.
